2. Template is a full description of object. User should be able to create object from template without specifying any params.

commit_message:
Check node_groups when creating cluster template

When users creating cluster template, they must not only
select 'node group template', but also decide how many
nodes what to launch.

This patch only fix server part, leaving the GUI check later
Partially Closes-Bug: #1250555

Change-Id: I5bae84484dfb9e1e0c7380590105a31d116b3b4c

Looks OK, but I am no expert in this bit.'}, {'account_id': 7069, 'date': '2013-11-08 03:57:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-11-13 14:33:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Do not merge

This doesn't bump the object version to account for this change. It also doesn't add support for backleveling the object to versions prior to this which were restricted to strings.

Further, I think that a "Dict of JSON blobs" is just a hack to allow you to store whatever you want into the extra_info.

Personally, I think that this should be left as DictOfStrings and that we shouldn't just support stashing arbitrary junk into that field. However, if it needs to be this complex, then I think you need to:

1. Make it a top-level JSON blob
2. Bump the version
3. Support backleveling it to the old format (which will be impossible to do fully, AFAIK)

Without #3, you earn the distinction of being the first thing to break live upgrade for icehouse :('}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2013-11-15 18:00:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Dan, thanks for your comments and suggestion.

It's ok to use the DictOfStrings for the extra info, however, we have to consider the situation that currently there is one non-string value (it's list) in the extra_info dict for 'phys_func" key (that means the change to DictOfStrings has already break the PciDevice), although we can limit to string for future usage.


We can have several choice:


a) migrate the DB to change that value to be a string in database, that means we will really be the first one to break the live upgrade.


b) Use DictOfStrings, but add a hack in the object, so that if the key in the dict is the 'phys_func', then we translate it to be json string, otherwise be string. This is in fact a hack to option 1, and I think it's also the purpose of object, that we don't need migrate the database, but handle everything in the object.


c) use the json blob as current yongli's patch. I'm not sure if we need back-level support the old format of DictOfString, which in fact break this object.


your idea?

--jyh'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-11-18 18:38:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

It was DictOfStrings already, although I know that got added shortly after Icehouse opened. Are you saying there's something that actually stores lists into the blob in grizzly? I distinctly remember complaining about this unrestrained nature of the extra bits and asked for care to be used :/

I think the way forward is to migrate the data "live" in the object, and support back-leveling to the old format in some way (is there a single key we can predict?) in obj_make_compatible().'}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2013-11-18 18:49:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Yes, there is a list in blob in H release and I know someone is, or plan to, utilize that H feature.


Originally we think the extra info has to be very complex to support the network SR-IOV. Yongli had discussion with Neutron guys at summit, and seems it will be simpler than our expectation thus the string should meet the requirement.


Luckily there is only one key and and we can back compatible with it through object. We will work as your suggestion.


All your warnings in advance become reality in the end, most of the warnings fixed during the development, this missed one becomes big trouble in the end, sigh.


Thanks
--jyh'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-11-26 06:03:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-11-26 06:03:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}]

pci passthrough: store json in extra info key value pair

Unicode object support need know the exactly type of the value store
in the objects. Store PCI device extra info value as a json string,
so that Unicode is handled correctly.

Huawei HVS driver supports QOS and Tier functions. User can
open those functions by setting volume type. QOS requires users
to set flow strategy and io priority. Tier requires user to set
distribution policy and transfer strategy.

The current driver limits the QOS strategy to be "Qos-high",
"Qos-normal" and "Qos-low" which is not direct, and just allows
user to set distribution policy: "Tier-high", "Tier-normal" and
"Tier-low".

This patch changes the keys of QOS and Tier and adds transfer
strategy for Tier. Also it checks QOS strategy status when adding
new lun to the strategy.

Change-Id: Ib3daabc3a68da47d81b53857d3080158b5b574f4

commit_message:
Fix huawei HVS driver QoS and Tier issues

Huawei HVS driver supports QOS and Tier functions. User can
open those functions by setting volume type. QOS requires users
to set flow strategy and io priority. Tier requires user to set
distribution policy and transfer strategy.

The current driver limits the QOS strategy to be "Qos-high",
"Qos-normal" and "Qos-low" which is not direct, and just allows
user to set distribution policy: "Tier-high", "Tier-normal" and
"Tier-low".

This patch changes the keys of QOS and Tier and adds transfer
strategy for Tier. Also the driver checks QOS strategy status
when adding new LUN to the strategy, or it will fail to add new
LUN to the strategy.

DocImpact
The reference document for Huawei cinder driver has contained these
changes. So this patch needs to backport to Havana.

Closes-bug: #1237268
Change-Id: Ib3daabc3a68da47d81b53857d3080158b5b574f4

commit_message:
handle empty network info in instance cache

The nw_info value [] was being incorrectly equated with None. This caused
infinite recursion when api._get_instance_nw_info returned [] and was wrapped
with @refresh_cache (e.g., _get_instance_nw_info in
nova.network.neutronv2.api.API).

Fixes bug #1251792.

Change-Id: I3034fbb20e790f2d6f22c50b74a9f9dcdf9081aa

commit_message:
xenapi: move session into new client module

This is the start of building a set of objects on top of the XenAPI
library to make a clear separation between XenAPI client and
business logic.

This is all the first steps towards pull out the client lib into oslo
incubator, so we can share code between Nova and Cinder.

DocImpact
While there is a change to the sample config file, there is no change in
the content of the config file.

Part of blueprint xenapi-driver-refactor
Change-Id: I463923a9ee289ff4b86fcf26d8c656609685857e

commit_message:
Replace removed items in Python3

Built-in function xrange and type long were used in Python 2,
were removed in Python3. Python3 uses range and int. Here we use
six.moves.range and six.integer_types.

Implements: blueprint make-python3-compatible
Change-Id: I770de45f6178086abe54e2aca2b554c14c68c00e

commit_message:
Periodic task _poll_unconfirmed_resizes can now use slave db

This allows the _poll_unconfirmed_resizes periodic task to use the
slave db for reads if the deployment has a slave configured. For
slaveless deployments behavior remains unchanged.

This commit advances the MigrationList object to version 1.1

Change-Id: I10bf729e92dc599819ef74a97a834c7f2df5b162
Partially-implements: blueprint periodic-tasks-to-db-slave

Rename _get_vm_state to _get_vm_status

The method is actually used to get the server's "status", so rename it

commit_message:
Forced isolation for the tests in test_list_servers_negative.py

In bug 1252971, race condition will arise if the allow_tenant_isolation
is false. ListServersNegativeTestJSON and ListServersNegativeTestXML
will share the tenant, if both of them check if there are existing servers
or not before both of them create new servers, the actual servers will
be double of the expected.
this also removes the redundant code in this files.

Closes-bug: 1252971

Change-Id: I2f859057a71ccada86b5733c1a27386fcd6bc4b5

'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-10-29 20:06:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(3 inline comments)

I think there is a lot of no-op going on in the tests for the mock on deallocate_for_instance which should be addressed differently.

At a higher level, when we step back, I'm not sure this is even the right approach to fixing the problem.  I have a feeling that when the instance doesn't get a host and is failed, it should be in error state rather than deleted, I think the change from error to deleted state is just fixing a symptom of the changes-since problem that you're trying to fix.  So rather than changing the API, maybe it makes more sense to fix changes-since to work with error'ed instances that don't have a host?"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-10-29 20:10:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

In other words, I think the changes-since might be working as designed. The bug report points to the docs that says:

"To allow clients to keep track of changes, the changes-since filter displays items that have been recently deleted. Both images and servers contain a DELETED status that indicates that the resource has been removed."

But I think that's probably for user-initiated deleted instances, not failed instances. I could be wrong there though.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-10-29 20:20:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

If anything I think this just needs to set the instance.vm_state before calling destroy(), although I'm not sure if that is really warranted. I think that DELETED is probably only currently reachable via a user asking for it, so having something go to DELETED on behalf of the system itself seems like a weird transition to me.

Falling back to local delete doesn't seem right to me at all though. Also, there's probably a cells component here that needs to be resolved."}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-10-30 20:12:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Hi Dan, 

About your comment:     

    "having something go to DELETED on behalf of the system itself seems like a weird transition to me"

With this patch we are not deleting the instance on behalf of the system we are only ensuring that instance deletions are consistent even when the instance had no host. The deletion request comes in from the user for deleting a failed instance.

When deleting instances we were doing a separate deletion code path for failed instance with no hosts (the one under the "if not host") and that code path was not kept up to date with the regular delete path. As you can see it was only invoking instance.destroy() but the rest of the deletion logic such as removing the instance from the cache and doing _do_delete() was not getting invoked. It makes sense that an instance that failed for not having a host, is considered a "local instance" and deleted as such, with the existing code for doing that, since that instance really only exists in the db.

With the current code before the patch, a deletion that went through the "no host" path, ended up looking differently than a deletion that did go through the regular local_delete() path, and this is affecting API consumers because the API documentation clearly says that any deleted server will show up as DELETED on a Changes-Since API request (http://docs.openstack.org/api/openstack-compute/2/content/ChangesSince.html) which is true in all cases except when the instance failed due to no host.

Thank you,'}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-10-30 21:25:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: (3 inline comments)

commit_message:
Ensure deleted instances' status is always DELETED

Currently when deleting failed instances that were never assigned a
host, their vm_state is left in 'error' instead of 'deleted'. This is a
problem when invoking the Index Instances REST API with a Changes-Since
query parameter since that API returns both deleted and non-deleted
instances, but currently the failed deleted instances are incorrectly
marked as status:ERROR instead of status:DELETED.

This patch modifies the server ViewBuilder to ensure the status is
correctly set.

Change-Id: I614714676bab4986564b236d74f2c0d77400e48c
Closes-bug: #1243301

commit_message:
Enable non-ascii characters in flavor names

The current implementation provided under commit e6b42d made it so that
flavor names did not have special characters (e.g. *&^%$ etc. except for
-._ and space) however it also limited names to only ascii letters.

This patch makes it so that special characters are still not allowed,
except the ones currently allowed, but it allows the use of non-ascii
characters so that flavor names can be created in locales other than
English.

Change-Id: I056451a5e8b7a49f86e0a11d0011393dc769db34
Closes-bug: #1241625

commit_message:
Make baremetal_deploy_helper understand ephemeral disks

Teach baremetal_deploy_helper how to run sfdisk with ephemeral disks.
baremetal_deploy_helper calls default mkfs on the epheral disk.

Change-Id: I92d473c34e9a076f5dbcd54be538410b30b10204
Partial-Bug: #1238311
Co-Authored-By: Robert Collins <rbtcollins@hp.com>

commit_message:
Extend LibvirtConfigGuest to parse guest cpu element info

Add support for LibvirtConfigGuest to parse LibvirtConfigGuestCPU,
parse CPU element 'mode' and 'match' from dom. This is the first
step to improve live migration CPU compare check.

Change-Id: Iab92b38afeade9876be391584e4e41864641134a

commit_message:
Enhance tests for flavor_extra_spec API

1) Test for GET {flavor_id}/os-extra_specs/{key_id}
2) Add a negative test to test extra spec key update

Change-Id: I0d424005586f0bcc27642fa9124c7e35a99f8724

subject: Add test for update/reset_snapshot_status API

commit_message:
Run df after gate

In order to make sure we aren't getting close to filling up disks lets
run 'df -h' after every devstack run and log the output.

Change-Id: Ia378cb68109af0af49e8fa45a784f54ef16f327c

commit_message:
Adds support for json output to nova client

This change adds an option --json to the cli which enables
output as a json formatted string. This will be helpful
for automating scripts using the cli client.

Change-Id: I1b4bc687eb53db36cdeb0cd93ea6578355fea887
Closes-Bug: #1254351

commit_message:
Work around neutron floatingip race condition

Neutron has a problem where neutron-server will only return externally
visible networks after the service has started sometimes. In order to
deal with that we are ssh'ing into the controller node and restarting
neutron-server before trying to create a floatingip. We try for two
minutes before giving up.

Change-Id: Ia4e476339a3d73a8c13ca898e0f0b582adc53828
Related-Bug: #1254555

When trying to create or update a subnet from the Networks
details page, the tab titles 'Subnet' and 'Subnet details'
are not showing as translated. This patch add the missing
underscore.

Change-Id: I48cd47e7ead3717d96e4808f41bf876a567c8052
Closes-Bug: #1254026
(cherry picked from commit 599c2135e5dfdcf88324faf1a8336a252db72d2f)

commit_message:
translate text: "subnet"/"subnet details"

When trying to create or update a subnet from the Networks
details page, the tab titles 'Subnet' and 'Subnet details'
are not showing as translated. This patch add the missing
underscore.

Change-Id: I48cd47e7ead3717d96e4808f41bf876a567c8052
Closes-Bug: #1254026
(cherry picked from commit 599c2135e5dfdcf88324faf1a8336a252db72d2f)

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-11 19:08:19.000000000', 'message': 'Add a specialized Event Type model and db table

As the events API gets fleshed out and more robust,
it will become increasingly necessary to ensure that the
database schema modeling events has the ability to quickly
retrieve a list of event types. With the current schema
having a foreign key from event to unique_name (the
monolithic generic string key lookup table), in order to
get a simple list of event types, one needs to do the following:

SELECT DISTINCT e.unique_name FROM event;

Not only is this inefficient, but the readability of the
model and database schema suffers from the generalization of
the unique name field relationship. With this patch, a new
event_type table -- as a specialization of unique_name -- is
added to the schema to allow for quick and easy lookups of
event types. This will lead to future ability to categorize
event types with ease. Instead of adding columns to the
monolithic unique_name table, we would only need to add a foreign
key relationship to the new event_type table tying the event_type
to a future event_type_class table...

Change-Id: I6e630ec534f16ba1bb9370d1859ae7640fc6b05b
Partial-Bug: 1211015

As the events API gets fleshed out and more robust,
it will become increasingly necessary to ensure that the
database schema modeling events has the ability to quickly
retrieve a list of event types. With the current schema
having a foreign key from event to unique_name (the
monolithic generic string key lookup table), in order to
get a simple list of event types, one needs to do the following:

SELECT DISTINCT e.unique_name FROM event;

Not only is this inefficient, but the readability of the
model and database schema suffers from the generalization of
the unique name field relationship. With this patch, a new
event_type table is added to the schema to allow for quick
and easy lookups of event types like so:

SELECT id, desc FROM event_type;

This will lead to future ability to categorize
event types with ease. Instead of adding columns to the
monolithic unique_name table, we would only need to add a foreign
key relationship to the new event_type table tying the event_type
to a future event_type_class table...

it will become increasingly necessary to ensure that the
database schema modeling events has the ability to quickly
retrieve a list of event types. With the current schema
having a foreign key from event to unique_name (the
monolithic generic string key lookup table), in order to
get a simple list of event types, one needs to do the following:

SELECT DISTINCT e.unique_name FROM event;

Not only is this inefficient, but the readability of the
model and database schema suffers from the generalization of
the unique name field relationship. With this patch, a new
event_type table is added to the schema to allow for quick
and easy lookups of event types like so:

SELECT id, desc FROM event_type;

This will lead to future ability to categorize
event types with ease. Instead of adding columns to the
monolithic unique_name table, we would only need to add a foreign
key relationship to the new event_type table tying the event_type
to a future event_type_class table...

commit_message:
Add a specialized Event Type model and db table

As the events API gets fleshed out and more robust,
it will become increasingly necessary to ensure that the
database schema modeling events has the ability to quickly
retrieve a list of event types. With the current schema
having a foreign key from event to unique_name (the
monolithic generic string key lookup table), in order to
get a simple list of event types, one needs to do the following:

SELECT DISTINCT e.unique_name FROM event;

Not only is this inefficient, but the readability of the
model and database schema suffers from the generalization of
the unique name field relationship. With this patch, a new
event_type table is added to the schema to allow for quick
and easy lookups of event types like so:

SELECT id, desc FROM event_type;

This will lead to future ability to categorize
event types with ease. Instead of adding columns to the
monolithic unique_name table, we would only need to add a foreign
key relationship to the new event_type table tying the event_type
to a future event_type_class table...

This patch also renames "event_name" to "event_type" everywhere
to avoid confusion.

Change-Id: I6e630ec534f16ba1bb9370d1859ae7640fc6b05b
Partial-Bug: 1211015

clearer.

commit_message:
Wait for o-r-c on nova compute as well.

We have seen situations where nova-compute is not ready when notcompute
has run its waitcondition. That leads to  errors while we fail to boot
instances until there is at least one nova compute available.

We also update nova-compute-instance.yaml so that it continues to work
stand-alone.

Change-Id: Iadea7a34e2cd4576cc78659b99c12e1041af5b45

commit_message:
Add option --image-size.

Adds an option for --image-size, which sets the DIB_IMAGE_SIZE
environment variable.  Having the cli option makes disk-image-create
more consistent in that parameters are able to be specified via a flag
on the command line or an environment variable.  Also, you may not be
able to remember all the environment variables that you can tweak, yet
--help will tell you about the cli parameters.  Preserves the old
behavior as well where if DIB_IMAGE_SIZE is set in your environment, it
will be honored.

Change-Id: I195c9144a80ce7b8bd5809b57f2bed71a2cbdf26

commit_message:
Enable test_create_backup

Since test_create_backup started to be tested, the next test
"test_get_console_output" failed many times. The reason would
be two image deletions at the end of test_create_backup.
This patch makes test_get_console_output avoids heavy workload
from test_create_backup by waiting for image deletions.

Related-Bug: #1251920
Change-Id: I4e2a04d14d1d85ad0dd4487e095239d73c48dbb4

[{'created': '2013-11-25 16:49:53.000000000', 'message': "Save the output from boot-seed-vm

We currently write the output of building the undercloud and overcloud
images to log files, this commit adds logging to the building of the
seed image.

The output from the disk-image-create contained in boot-seed-vm is
already saved to ~/.cache/image-create/image-file-cache but it doesn't
contain the output from all of boot-seed-vm and can be hard to find if
you don't know about it.

Change-Id: I3e75605fc889638fa77b1c1a5d46c6294fd101ea
"}]
commit_message:
Save the output from boot-seed-vm

We currently write the output of building the undercloud and overcloud
images to log files, this commit adds logging to the building of the
seed image.

The output from the disk-image-create contained in boot-seed-vm is
already saved to ~/.cache/image-create/image-file-cache but it doesn't
contain the output from all of boot-seed-vm and can be hard to find if
you don't know about it.

Change-Id: I3e75605fc889638fa77b1c1a5d46c6294fd101ea

commit_message:
Remove the dependency on oslo.config

Client libraries shouldn't depend on specific configuration libraries,
since that will make it difficult for other applications to adopt the
library.

This patch replaces all oslo.config usages with dictionaries. The client
will use those as options holders and all parameters are considered
optional.

Notice that `options` was preferred instead of `**options` since this
dictionary is considered a 'config object' and not a set of optional
parameters. This will make it easier for applications using
marconiclient to hold a single, mutable instance of options to pass
around.

Partially-Implements blueprint python-marconiclient-v1

Change-Id: Ib41f2957689545f05dab19338842fd9a953f2f76

Lifeless: The templates here are good to go. There is no way the changes I've introduced here should have added 'notcomputeImage' into the templates:

https://github.com/openstack/tripleo-heat-templates/blob/master/merge.py#L150"}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-11-25 07:01:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

Just noticed one thing inline - PowerUserName doesn't need to be in undercloud-source.yaml

Agree that it's very hard to double check the results here, but I don't see anything obviously wrong. I concentrated on comparing the source files (e.g. undercloud-source.yaml to original undercloud-{vm,bm}.yaml)

The notcomputeImage thing is merge.py prepending the name of the resource which uses it:

            if 'image' in MERGABLE_TYPES[rbody['Type']]:
                ikey = '%sImage' % (role)
                end_template['Resources'][role]['Properties'][image_key] = {'Ref': ikey}
                end_template['Parameters'][ikey] = ikey_val

If notcompute is misleading here, isn't the resource name misleading too?"}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-11-25 14:14:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-25 14:14:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

Yeah. The fact that we have 'notcomputeImage' in our template is an interaction between merge.py and the resource names we use in the undercloud (i.e. notcompute...).

Perhaps further refactoring is needed to address these concerns but I'm not convinced they belong in *this* commit.

commit_message:
Use merge.py for the undercloud templates.

This will require some changes to our devtest scripts
and TOCI to ensure we build the overcloud-vm template
before attempting to use it.

commit_message:
Add element for tripleo-heat-templates.

Installs tripleo-heat-templates from git under /opt/stack using the
source-repositories element.  The tuskar element is currently doing this
on it's own in order to get access to the templates, and I'd like to see
it in a seperate element instead.  Other consumers may want access to
the templates outside of using tuskar.  Will submit another change to
update the tuskar element to use this element once merged.

Change-Id: Ibfc61f4f677f051f409cbfef571c1da67356e440

commit_message:
Don't log to stdout when log_dir is set

In addition to checking if log_file is set, we should check
for log_dir as well. Previously, If log_file is not set, oslo
will output logs to stdout even if log_dir is set. The only way
for example the Heat folks avoided logging to stdout was to
set log_file, but then all the heat processes ended up logging
to the same file. So a check for both log_dir and log_file
should avoid any output to stdout. Please note that use_stderr
should be set to false as well to avoid any output to console

Change-Id: Ie2886da679daedea0197ee3b3963ebedb8f11a0b
Closes-Bug: #1226287

commit_message:
Remove instruction to stop mysql before db restore

The database restore using the mysql client can not succeed if the mysql
service is not running. As a result the errant direction to stop the
mysql service before running the client command has been removed.

Change-Id: Idf75f40cb2b86948381bd4c08b2e492fe15a7e2e
Closes-Bug: #1252902

commit_message:
Move openapproved into the reviewstats namespace.

This involves updating one of the shell scripts which now depends on
'pip install -e .' or 'pip install reviewstats' (for a release) having
been run.

Hi, Phil, there is case for an neutron port that owned by non-admin user, and admin-user assign a security-group that owned by admin to that port. So that means user can get that security-groups by get servers without all-tennats, but with your patch, it can't get. That looks like break the v2 api compatibility.

I think we should improve 'nova.network.security_group.neutron_driver.SecurityGroupAPI.get_instance_security_groups'.

'get_instance_security_groups' didn't get all port. it list the port with 'device_id'. so the performance problem is it get all security-groups. We can just get the security-groups with 'id' filters. like this: 'v2.0/security-groups.json?id=xxx&id=xxx'. The 'id' come from the 'security_groups' attribute of port."}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2013-09-23 15:49:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

This isn't actually directly related to the change I'm making - it's unchanged existing code which I think has to stay as it is"}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2013-09-29 02:45:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

Hi, Phil, How about we just improve neutron secgroup driver's 'get_instances_security_groups_bindings' as below:

ids = []

for port in ports:

    ids.append(port['id'])


search_opts['id'] = ids

security_groups = neutron.list_security_groups(**search_opts).get(security_groups)


That looks like more effective.

We needn't filter as tenant. And add filter as tenant more like some small feature."}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2013-09-29 20:35:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Alex,

Not quite sure I follow you - I still need to add the search_opts to neutron.list_ports() I think otherwise for a Neutron admin it will return a list of all of the ports in the system.   So I think that bit has to stay.

Does list_security_groups() accept a list of port_ids as 'id' in search potions ?  That sounds more like you'd be asking it for a specific set of security group IDs.  If it was to take a search option for port_id I'd expect it to me more like 'port_id' - but I couldn't see anything in the Neutron code that suggested it supported that as a search option in this method."}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2013-09-29 20:44:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Alex: I just tried passing in {'id': <list of port ids>} as search opts into neutron.list_security_groups() and it doens't return anything.

I understand the idea, but I don't think you can search for security groups that way ;-("}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2013-09-30 02:04:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Phil, For list ports, neutron support query like this:
"/v2.0/ports.json?device_id=<instance_id>&device_id=<instance_id>"

For list security_groups, neutron support query like this:
/v2.0/security-groups.json?id=<secgrp_id>&id=<secgrp_id>"

neutron client should support pass params like this: {"id": [...]}'}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2013-09-30 02:08:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Phil, this is the output on my machine, http://paste.openstack.org/show/47681/'}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2013-09-30 08:46:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Alex:  So what you're suggesting is that for list_ports() I could pass in the device_ids as search options (I assume that must be {'device_id': <list of id>}  - not 'id' as that would suggest a list of port ids no ?

However I'm worried that the list of device_ids in the search_opts could then be very long on a large system (its still possible that the list of servers is *all* servers on the system) - so I'm worried that this would sometimes blow the request limit.  My current approach still feels more robust to me (and I know it works on a very large system).

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-20 23:01:46.000000000', 'message': 'Fix performance of Server List with Neutron for Admins

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/30048/ optimized the
SecurityGroupsOutputController for the case where the server
list only contains one server, but in all other cases the current
code calls the Neutron driver in a way that makes it retrieve
all ports and security groups visible to the tenant.

For users with a Neutron admin role this retrieves all ports
and SecGroups in the system, which on a large system is a
major performance issue and often leads to client timeouts.
Normally these users have further qualified their query to a
specific tenant or host, or maybe just trying to get their own
list of servers.

This change introduces a number of further optimizations
which address these cases.

1) If there a specific tenant is specified in the search options
of the request the Neutron queries are limited to this tenant

2) If all-tenants is not specified in the search options of the
request the Neutron queries are limited to the tenant making
the request.  This prevents a user with a Neutron admin role
from triggering an inadvertent query of all ports and
Sec Groups.

3) If a specific host is specified in the search options the
Sec Groups of each server are queried individually.  On
anything apart from a very small system this is more
efficient that getting all ports and Sec Groups and filtering
to the specific servers.

In addition when getting the Sec Groups of a specific server
the tenant_id is explicitly passed to the Neutron Driver so that
and the query scoped to that tenant.  As above this prevents a
user with a Neutron admin role from triggering an inadvertent
query of all ports and Sec Groups.

Fixes Bug: 1228384

Change-Id: I6f72533056e4f336f7578cc883fd1a125c2048a9

commit_message:
Fix performance of Server List with Neutron for Admins

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/30048/ optimized the
SecurityGroupsOutputController for the case where the server
list only contains one server, but in all other cases the current
code calls the Neutron driver in a way that makes it retrieve
all ports and security groups visible to the tenant.

For users with a Neutron admin role this retrieves all ports
and all SecGroups in the system, which on a large system is a
major performance issue and often leads to client timeouts.
Normally these users have further qualified their query to a
specific tenant or host, or are maybe just trying to get their
own list of servers.

If instead we pass the pre-filtered list of servers to Neutron
it can query for ports associated with just the device IDs of
the servers.  We then use that list of ports to build a
specific list of security groups IDs to query for.

This approach means that we can remove the initial
optimization for a single server case.

Closes-Bug: 1228384

Change-Id: I6f72533056e4f336f7578cc883fd1a125c2048a9

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-28 21:41:07.000000000', 'message': "Include name/level in unit test log messages

Use a more informative format than just the raw message string in log
messages captured by fixtures.FakeLogger during unit testing.  For
example, this changes cryptic unit test output such as

    pythonlogging:'': {{{
    214 -> 215...
    done
    215 -> 216...
    done
    }}}

into:

    pythonlogging:'': {{{
    INFO [migrate.versioning.api] 214 -> 215...
    INFO [migrate.versioning.api] done
    INFO [migrate.versioning.api] 215 -> 216...
    INFO [migrate.versioning.api] done
    }}}

which instantly makes it clearer that these numbers come from database
migrations.

Change-Id: I56b6fa03892e6d865ccb036fdf75d2bb499b6c93
"}]

@Tal:
I'm not sure what you mean by quite tedious. It's a leading character which is very simple to remove. (both manually and with a script, which is where I'm assuming your concern is coming from)

Also having every option commented out is the right starting place for tools that are using the sample. It ensures that the default values specified in the code are accurate. If we didn't comment out the lines then when a sample is copied to be really used it ensures the defaults are actually used. If the lines were not commented out we would just be overwriting the default setting with what we hope is the proper default specified in the sample. This can be a big problem in certain scenarios for example if we are doing upgrade testing."}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-11-25 15:45:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

commit_message:
Add sample config check to tox pep8 job

This commit takes the check_uptodate.sh script from nova and adds it
to the pep8 tox job. This will enforce that the sample config file is
up to date for each proposed commit. This also ensures that config
options are setup properly and that the style in the sample config is
consistent because it's auto-generated.

Partially Implements: blueprint config-cleanup

Change-Id: I9efaa9fc1cf09e95d7111b000895c7b49705713b

commit_message:
Move admin client initialization into stress-openstack

Running the stress test framework without any tempest.conf causes
an error. This is due to the fact that the admin client expects the
configuration file. This causes error while doing pep8 checks (see
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56308/)

Change-Id: I69b3d83185d1b144474314402ad5449980d6ffbc
Fixes: bug #1251663

commit_message:
Apply hybrid vif dirver based on security group api config

Security group with neutron OVS is no longer working, because
hybrid driver isn't selected.
In this commit, we are going to select hybrid driver based only
security group api configration.

Closes bug: 1252620

Change-Id: Ic0bfc2e4e90bc6241f8af256ab122bc561a85b78

commit_message:
Serve local mirror using apache

There are enough behavioral differences between http and file urls
for pypi mirrors that we should do the local mirror via apache. That
way we're testing what we care about - consumption of changes in the
mirror context - and not what we don't - how well pip deals with file
urls.

Change-Id: Icb16e8bbe77c03f224d06010eeb6bd0877b0d6ca

commit_message:
Remove vim header

No need to set tabstop 189 times, this can be set in your vimrc file
instead.  Also if set incorrectly gate (pep8 check) will catch your
mistakes.

Change-Id: Ic6f0c0ef94e8194a5c121598305d1ec3c74e4843

'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2013-11-15 16:21:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(3 inline comments)

Ideally I'd have a config error be raised if catch_errors is not at head of pipeline, rather than have it inserted automatically. Apart from being less surprising/confusing, this would mean that catch_errors (or other mandatory middleware following this pattern) could still have config sections in the conf file. But that is going to cause a lot of grief.

How about searching the constructed app pipeline for catch errors (the class, not the config section), if found then move it to front of pipeline (same instance, so config not lost). If not found, then insert a new instance (as current patch does).

This way, any piece of mandatory middleware that is config'd in wrong order can be re-ordered without losing its local conf, and any future middleware accidentally using catch_errors for its config section doesn't get mysteriously erased, because test is against class type, not config label."}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2013-11-15 18:22:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

(1 inline comment)

One further suggestion inline. Not been able to validate by coding up, so apologies if it is a red herring.'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-11-15 18:55:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Work In Progress

Working out some of the kinks still. Feel free to comment even still.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2013-11-18 18:51:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I had a go at hacking the pipeline context, this seems to work (cut from swift.common.wsgi.py):

http://paste.openstack.org/show/grKBWs38cUWrls67gPNg/

...forces existing filter to start of pipeline, or inserts, based on module name'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-11-25 17:45:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (3 inline comments)

> Ideally I'd have a config error be raised if catch_errors is not at head of pipeline, rather than have it inserted automatically.

What I am (perhaps feebly) trying to suggest is to take it out of the
hands of the user where catch-errors lives in the pipeline, just
making the catch-errors behavior more of an extension of what the app
provides rather than pure middleware.

To that end, I was considering ignoring existing catch-errors that
reference the middleware and just making it be based on the
proxy-server configuration for logging.

> Apart from being less surprising/confusing, this would mean that catch_errors (or other mandatory middleware following this pattern) could still have config sections in the conf file.

In light of the proxy-server (or any other app server) this gives the
user a false sense of control, as what they put in the pipeline is not
obeyed. As such, I would remove the catch_errors entry point from
setup.cfg so that it is no longer available.

> But that is going to cause a lot of grief. How about searching the constructed app pipeline for catch errors (the class, not the config section), if found then move it to front of pipeline (same instance, so config not lost). If not found, then insert a new instance (as current patch does). This way, any piece of mandatory middleware that is config'd in wrong order can be re-ordered without losing its local conf, and any future middleware accidentally using catch_errors for its config section doesn't get mysteriously erased, because test is against class type, not config label.

It might be better to just pull catch_errors as a configurable piece
middleware entirely and make it only directly referenced by the
various pieces of code providing WSGI applications."}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-11-25 17:46:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Abandoning in favor of Alistair's work."}]

commit_message:
Ensure catch_errors is always the first filter

Ensure that for the proxy-server the catch_errors filter is always the
first (or left most if reading the pipeline list from the
proxy-server.conf file).

Not only do we ensure it is first, we also ensure that it is always
present.

Change-Id: I987923bcfb1e666c087e7eafe3fc18db1ce90208
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

Currently, if a user performs a BatchAction that is not
allowed, a 'You do not have permission' message is
returned.  However, there may be other reasons why
an action is disallowed (an object in a non-deletable
state, for instance).  This patch genericizes the

commit_message:
Update 'action_not_allowed' message to be more generic

Currently, if a user performs a BatchAction that is not
allowed, a 'You do not have permission' message is
returned.  However, there may be other reasons why
an action is disallowed (an object in a non-deletable
state, for instance).  This patch genericizes the
'not allowed' message.

Closes-Bug: #1173870
Change-Id: I4bb58afd1442edd719750b0d325cc7efa14026e3

commit_message:
add tests for InstanceUsageAuditLog

this adds both positive and negative tests for the
following client:
GET /v2/{tenant_id}/os-instance_usage_audit_log/%s
GET /V2/{tenant_id}/os-instance_usage_audit_log

also adds corresponding xml and json rest client

commit_message:
port attach_interfaces and server_address tests into v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I184874147cc872a42fb34f89f5ebe8bd763773b4

commit_message:
Added images support and existing config support

This adds the support of auto configuring images to be used by
tempest by either using existing images in glance or in case they
do not exist, download the cirros images and register them.
Also, added the option of specifing a config file instead of
relying on the sample

Change-Id: I436d2a75706fdaa294a92d0fd38ea3269c776e8c

commit_message:
Fixes trove-api daemon fake mode functionality.

This commit adds code to register taskmanager as a fake endpoint.
This allows the fake daemon to work again.

Fixes bug 1238901
Change-Id: Icb7c97cad3d76dc36a38126eb7f8b5929dc0d591

commit_message:
Set SERVICE_PROTOCOL in keystone

This was incorrectly not being used in the devstack case and is needed
in grenade before the fix can be made in devstack.

Change-Id: Ia7533e41bc4fdf932a9d565a20b7e1c1107f37c3

"The volume ID and authorization code are securely delivered to the end-client, by the company." from https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/VolumeTransfer.

And the situation's also confrimed by the cinder's codes.

So maybe I need to remove the 'list' operation in 'test_create_get_list_accept_volume_transfer'? Or do it like PS9, or even PS7?

commit_message:
Add test cases for volume-transfer

Volume-transfer is involved in Havana Release in Cinder now.
We need to complete related test cases for it.

Fixes bug: 1243070

Change-Id: Ie00aed32ebed70a3f5fcb5c5b5c16a2ae8e4549c

Is support for UUID tokens in general deprecated?  If so maybe we should remove all of that and not just the option setting?'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2013-11-18 17:03:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Dean - UUID tokens are not deprecated, and I don't think there's any plan to deprecate them. If there was a suggestion to remove UUID token format support I'd push back on that since there's some question as to if PKI tokens are the best option in all cases.

I tried this change with KEYSTONE_TOKEN_FORMAT=UUID and it worked for me (I got back a UUID token with keystone token-get)."}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2013-11-18 17:05:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

If the question is more about if devstack needs to support UUID token config... that I'm not sure of."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-11-18 17:13:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Thanks Brant, that's what I needed, DevStack does need to continue to support UUID tokens as long as Keystone has them."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-25 14:53:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

commit_message:
Keystone don't use deprecated token_format option

devstack was setting the token_format option in the keystone
configuration file. This option is deprecated so should not be
used.

Change-Id: I047de155f0d9d2a1c009533c2f97f505cc80c6de

commit_message:
Check return code of command instead of checking stderr

Command "ip link show" return a no 0 return code when passing
a no existing ip interface so we should use the return code
instead of checking stderr because stderr can contain messages
from the system even though the command succeeded.

Change-Id: Ic43e72dab3c5b6e266240b7ff7309ca3b44f8ed5
Closes-Bug: #1248699

This adds a simple wrapper to call tempest volume tests.
The idea is to make it easy to execute and capture results
from tempest.api.volume.test_*

Concept is for drivers in Cinder to configure cinder.conf as
needed and then run this script which will restart services and
kick off the tempest tests, and capture the output to a logfile
for submission.

To run,
1. deploy devstack as normal with tempest included in enabled_services
2. modify cinder.conf appropriately for your driver
3. execute the script devstack/driver_certs/cinder_driver_cert.sh

Script *will* if you're not running from devstack TOP_DIR

commit_message:
Add driver_cert wrapper for cinder

This adds a simple wrapper to call tempest volume tests.
The idea is to make it easy to execute and capture results
from tempest.api.volume.test_*

Concept is for drivers in Cinder to configure cinder.conf as
needed and then run this script which will restart services and
kick off the tempest tests, and capture the output to a logfile
for submission.

To run,
1. deploy devstack as normal with tempest included in enabled_services
2. modify cinder.conf appropriately for your driver
3. execute the script devstack/driver_certs/cinder_driver_cert.sh

Change-Id: I98ec9e1e418a8416406db5e2e6ffd21992e392cf

commit_message:
Revert "Support building wheels (PEP-427)"

'universal=True' means app supports py2 and py3 which isn't supported by
climate at least due to the eventlet dependency, so, my bad, it should
be reverted atm. W/o 'universal=True' wheel bdist still could be built.

This reverts commit 415a66430b3c395c8f442d89f4d4ec6d48378276

Change-Id: I074b33f1a1df87c3f3cc58b5734b6f20e364de5b

commit_message:
Revert "Support building wheels (PEP-427)"

Monty Taylor said the following in [1]

This is incorrect. universal indicates that a created wheel works with
both py2 and py3. We can build wheels without this. Infra has patches
almost landed to create and upload wheels on every release

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/57172

Change-Id: I4240d851bbfe9a9e2f5022a008bf88eeacd09d8c

'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-07-24 11:56:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-07-24 12:36:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-07-26 09:51:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-07-29 06:42:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I think a lot of what you've done here is cleanup work that we need to do on both the rabbit and qpid drivers once we have some unit testing in place

See Ifb72853e83b678b311fecb21fe016af19a67b272 for how we can get started on the qpid driver with minimal changes in the same way I did the rabbit driver

Makes sense as a first step, I hope?"}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-07-29 11:35:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hey, 

yup, I did some clean-up but I was kind of forced to do it. I cleaned the connection thing before we decided to keep it as-is. When we decided that, I checked a bit the old connection code and IMHO, keeping it as-is will require some workarounds.

I also changed consumers and producers classes because I had to change the base class constructor - i.e: callback is not needed - so, I thought those changes were worth it. 

I think your patch might work - I haven't tested it - but TBH, it looks like an awful workaround to make this thing work. How long are we planning to keep that around before we work on clean-ups? I think we should clean all that code up before we release H-3, is that the plan?

TBH, The more I dig into the old RPC code, the less I think keeping it as-is makes sense. I'm afraid there are some corner cases we are not seeing in this integration. Thoughts?

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-07-29 11:35:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Work In Progress'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-07-29 11:48:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Flavio - yeah, I don't want to keep this as-is long-term

I'm thinking we'd at least want good unit test coverage of the drivers before doing substantial re-factoring. However, I'd probably also prefer the comfort of e.g. having Nova switched over to the oslo.messaging so we could bisect any Nova regression caused by the re-factoring.

I also want to hold off on re-factoring for a little so that it's easier to sync across any changes from oslo-incubator."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-11-22 23:22:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

This looks pretty stale ... should it be abandoned?"}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-11-25 16:01:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Abandoned

Yup, I kept it hoping we would've started refactoring this code sooner. I'll pick it up later if needed."}]

commit_message:
Set swift timeouts higher

Devstack is commonly run in a small slow environment, so bump the
timeouts up.

node_timeout is how long between read operations a node takes to
respond to the proxy server
conn_timeout is all about how long it takes a connect() system call to
return

Change-Id: Ib437466a3fc9274b8aa49b19e4fe7fa26f553419
Co-Authored-By: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>
Related-Bug: #1252514
(cherry picked from commit a2f2bba4eca9837a589acc1b5f22789915108b25)

[{'created': '2013-10-21 07:40:10.000000000', 'message': "Additional ssh tests with tempest

The run_ssh option is used on the default 'false',
 so several test case and validation step was disabled.

It was disabled because:
 * Admin password injection with the cirros image is not supported.
  (We 'cannot' inject password/shadow to a ram disk.)
 * In the current system setup floating IP is required for connecting
   with neutron

The run_ssh boolean option will be removed from tempest, it will be replaced
with ssh_connect_method and ssh_auth_method.

Since using a floating ip with nova flat network is not required in these
case, the 'fixed'/private IPs (ssh_connect_method) will be used with nova network
, and we will use the 'floating' IPs with neutron.

The default value of ssh_auth_method is keypair, it works in both cases.

Change-Id: I3d47811d801985687526749a430ed6db64224f99

commit_message:
Additional ssh tests with tempest

The run_ssh option is used on the default 'false',
 so several test case and validation step was disabled.

It was disabled because:
 * Admin password injection with the cirros image is not supported.
  (We 'cannot' inject password/shadow to a ram disk.)
 * In the current system setup floating IP is required for connecting
   with neutron

The run_ssh boolean option will be removed from tempest, it will be replaced
with ssh_connect_method and ssh_auth_method.

Since using a floating ip with nova flat network is not required in these
case, the 'fixed'/private IPs (ssh_connect_method) will be used with nova network
, and we will use the 'floating' IPs with neutron when the NAMESPACES
are enabled(default).

The default value of ssh_auth_method is keypair, it works in both cases.

Change-Id: I3d47811d801985687526749a430ed6db64224f99

Add new attributes for common rpc configuration

We need provide ability to configure the following rpc related
attributes:
rpc_thread_pool_size

backend.

commit_message:
fixup_stuff prettytable min version

The minimum prettytable version is changed from 0.6 to 0.7
 in the global requirements.

If the system has an older prettytable version the fixup_stuff does not
takes effect in time, because at fixup time the system has the old
version.

Ensure the fixup installs the minimum required version in time.

Change-Id: If1737dacb25db73b68e707953d05576ad8a97da7

commit_message:
Set nodes status to error in case of failed tasks (provisioning or deployment)
* update cluster status (and nodes statuses) even if task's wasn't changed
* don't update status to discover if node has status error

Change-Id: Iaafdb4c5f27807542e9e2a5183a531225868e37d
Closes-Bug: PRD-2381

commit_message:
Preserve Exception Message objects

In order for Accept-Language HTTP header to be used for exception
message localization, the openstack.common.gettextutils.Message
objects associated with the glance exceptions must be preserved
when the controllers raise WSGI HTTP exceptions.

Partially implements bp user-locale-api

Change-Id: Iafba6fa97869e7e29d7b43a84893904f34da3a25

commit_message:
Add support for API message localization

Add support for doing language resolution for a request, based on the
Accept-Language HTTP header.

The underscore (_) method is initialized so that it returns
openstack.common.gettextutils.Message objects. The locale
of these Message objects is set when exceptions with which
they are associated are raised in the context of an HTTP
request.

Partially implements bp user-locale-api

Change-Id: I15856c19cdafa0729b603634ffc95f10dbe90a1c

commit_message:
Issue brctl/delif only if the bridge exists

Add a check for existence of the bridge before we try cleaning
up as we see a lot of spurious exceptions in the logs especially
when rebuild_instance is in progress and terminate_instance is
issued

Closes-Bug: #1243488

Change-Id: Ib0e2e4d9506e3a8f63201d28a3fc2c910c77d3bd

commit_message:
Selectively import RPC backend retry config

Fixes bug 1244698

When setting the RPC publisher policies, selectively import
the retry config native to the configured RPC backend.

This avoid ImportErrors when all the dependencies of an unused
RPC backend are not installed locally.

Change-Id: If05a5a389a1b417875e0426fd83fb6d73d570487
(cherry picked from commit a8e12c0429516d477b40eb7106c3b160a29c965a)

commit_message:
Fix building of overcloud compute node image

Bulding of overcloud compute node image fails when trying
to remove the XML definition of libvirt default network
(there are no such files when raring base image is used).

Change-Id: I06b1cff827a978d81379c15b5e181262b52906b0

commit_message:
Fixes RequestContext initialization failure.

RequestContext initialization failed in nova because of the following
error:
"TypeError: 'in <string>' requires string as left operand, not NoneType"

It must traverses in tuple not in string when find the "volume" service_catalog.

Change-Id: Ie0de50fcafbeabf4698696add610d4e6804f45eb
Closes-Bug: #1248424

commit_message:
Add note for NoopFirewallDriver

Complement description and Configuration When Nova let Neutron to
handle the firewall.
Add case descrition when setting "firewall_driver = neutron.agent
.firewall.NoopFirewallDriver" both in Nova and Neutron.

Change-Id: I80211afaf335c8e50c72a907d6b15e9b5cbf7dd8
Closes-Bug: #1232965
(cherry picked from commit 650984d9156a324efd4e08c2e8065ca4b5d24d31)

with the older 1.X API to allow continuous deployment without any downtime.

The v2 rev of this API is really simple.  It removes the
get_backdoor_port() method, which was moved to the base rpc API common
to all services in havana.  It also removes some unused parameters.

UpgradeImpact - Deployments doing continuous deployment should follow this
process to upgrade without any downtime with the consoleauth service:

1) Sync all consoleauth services to this commit, so that they handle
   both new and old messages.

2) Upgrade everything else to this commit so that all clients start
   sending the new messages.

3) Upgrade past this, where support for the old messages will be
   dropped.

Part of blueprint rpc-major-version-updates-icehouse

commit_message:
Add V2 rpc api for console

Add support for the 2.0 console rpc API.  This commit retains compatibility
with the older 1.X API to allow continuous deployment without any downtime.

The v2 rev of this API is really simple.  It removes the
get_backdoor_port() method, which was moved to the base rpc API common
to all services in havana.  It also removes some unused parameters.

UpgradeImpact - Deployments doing continuous deployment should follow this
process to upgrade without any downtime with the consoleauth service:

1) Set [upgrade_levels] console=havana in your config.

2) Upgrade to this commit.

3) Once everything has been upgraded, remove the entry in
[upgrade_levels] so that all rpc clients to the nova-console service
start sending the new 2.0 messages.

Part of blueprint rpc-major-version-updates-icehouse

Change-Id: If05d041c5104b7f4e2e6b035de33cdd695c7a1ae

commit_message:
Clarify that boot-stack isn't only for baremetal

Seems we allow using boot-stack for running a baremetal or KVM OpenStack
but still mention baremetal in the first line of its description.

Change-Id: Ib5b772df44d5bd90999327c21c8ee07a4aa3f893

commit_message:
Fix migration with fkeys

Creation of fkeys doesn't work in sqlite, so we should do these
changes in another dialects.
Fix bug 1204823.

Also we can have a problem with data conflicted with declared ForeignKey.
We should dump "bad" data to another place, upgrade and create FK.
Downgrade method should restore dumped data.

Change-Id: I33089d6f47dcde4cf716a3d303c8df23dd19cd07

commit_message:
Decouple from Oslo uuidutils module

uuidutils module will be deprecated in Icehouse, So need replace it.
This patch uses str(uuid.uuid4()) instead of method generate_uuid.

Closes-Bug: #1253497
Change-Id: I35815544429c489096b4db3fa79a649f4cd9459f

commit_message:
Remove confusing text from description form

In the forms to update or create Images, the description
field contains "Additional information here..."
which isn't particular clear (it sounds like you should
click there to see more information) and is causing
inaccurate translations.
This hint text actually does not provide any information,
comparing with other fields.
Removing it.

Change-Id: I4c223a2b995aaa73f9cfcca56516baaaf1c72831
Closes-Bug: #1251199

commit_message:
Add consume_from_share method to HostState class

Modify FilterScheduler._schedule_share to call new new method
consume_from_share (it was calling consume_from_volume).

Add HostState.consume_from_share to host_manager.

Change-Id: I124674afe739ccf9648f91fcfbc63fd3be7caecc
Closes-Bug: #1253860

"test_runs_ordering_priority". Value of this entity is picking up from

testset controller output results. Unit tests have been updated.

Change-Id: Iaee818505d69ce813d70c9ed1d25a4fb528a6496
'}]
commit_message:
Fix test_runs ordering on ui

For testset model new field has been added with name
"test_runs_ordering_priority". Value of this entity is picking up from
__profile__ attribute of testset module and is using now for ordering of
testset controller output results. Unit tests have been updated.

Change-Id: Iaee818505d69ce813d70c9ed1d25a4fb528a6496

commit_message:
Add config option to limit image properties

This patch adds the image_property_quota config option. This allows a deployer
to limit the number of image properties allowed on an image. The default value
is 128, as is currently the limit enforced by nova. Users will only be able to
update an image if the result of the transaction would be under this limit.
This behavior is intended to be similar to 'quota_metadata_items' in nova.

This is for both Glance v1 and v2.

Fixes bug 1251518
docImpact

Change-Id: I4aa9504deae836404f11c9ada71a91f85caeba4c

Also adds 'availabilityzone' parameters to notcompute and
nova-compute-instance. Adds a new tuskar specific overcloud
source overcloud-tuskar-source.yaml which omits the standard
'NovaCompute0'. For more info about how this will all be used
by Tuskar see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/52045/

"}]
commit_message:
Tuskar specific edits to templates

Also adds 'availabilityzone' parameters to notcompute and
nova-compute-instance. Adds a new tuskar specific overcloud
source overcloud-tuskar-source.yaml which omits the standard
'NovaCompute0'. For more info about how this will all be used
by Tuskar see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/52045/

Change-Id: I1ef87c6de81a7dc58ac0a79045696e8327207e99

commit_message:
To fix test_get_dss_rp in test_vmware_vmdk.py

The test "test_get_dss_rp" in test_vmware_vmdk.py is not testing
the positive case as intended. Rather, it tests the negative case
(no datastores) which is already covered by
"test_get_dss_rp_without_datastores".

Change-Id: I5b4802e22218217e0338fc721fc0ce1efeaee4f1
Closes-Bug: #1251126

commit_message:
Remove dead code from test_get_volume_stats()

The _emulate_vgs_execute() routine is never called because the function
that calls it (get_all_volume_groups) is overridden to return fake
output without executing vgs.

Change-Id: I3d3f536f7d85128547dc9e758e3930412ebed121

commit_message:
Add greenthread.sleep() to parent wait()

Add an eventlet.greenthread.sleep() to wait() to keep
cinder-volume parent from looping after catching SIGTERM
and hogging the CPU. This was already added to the running
state but is missing from the SIGTERM caught state when
the parent waits to reap the child.

Change-Id: Ia871e31db5bf9ec4e86f926f8f6c4f0f4ecb7925
Closes-Bug: #1254089

commit_message:
Add configdrive option as ssh authentication strategy

Use keypair authentication with configdrive attached.
This kind of keypair strategy expected to work even if the
 metadata service not working.

Make the configdrive option as a default strategy.

Implements: blueprint ssh-auth-strategy

Change-Id: I828e2faf0b5f21b71626db8616335868a0b23c52

I don't think this change is the direction we need to be heading because we shouldn't be re-implementing inheritance (via __getattr__).  The commit message also mentions improvements to unit testing that are not contained in this file.  

I recommend holding off on the change because of the longer term discussion that needs to happen on composition in Quantum.   Based on conversations started at the last summit, I expect to hold a session or two on switching various parts of the codebase from inheritance to composition.  Switching to composition has its own tradeoffs too which we need to discuss and doing so for one service would be inconsistent as things are currently implemented."}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2013-06-24 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Restored'}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2013-06-24 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Rebased'}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2013-06-24 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2013-06-24 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Mark,

The primary goal of this change was to make plugin testable. 
I was not going to add tests in this patch, but there's clearly a need for plugin tests as we're moving towards adding plugin-drivers. 

Plus, with current inheritance model, plugin drivers will require some ugly proxy calls in lbaas plugin to lbaas DB plugin, I'd like to avoid that.

Could you share your thoughts on how to test DB-unrelated logic of lbaas plugin without switching to composition?

commit_message:
Decouple Loadbalancer plugin and Db plugin

fixes bug 1179468

Use composition instead of inheritance in loadbalancer plugin.
This way Db logic can be mocked easily in plugin unit test.
Plugin proxies missing calls to Db plugin via __getattr__

Change-Id: I7949fc7fd70c4a10c88eb00b4a5d1ac25c0d79d4

commit_message:
Explicit listing of Glance policies in json file

Most OpenStack components do list their policies in their policy.json but not
Glance. It will let user directly know what options is available to them.
Previously non-listed policy do follow the default rule now.
List of available policies have been taken from Developer Guide page :
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/glance/policies.html#constructing-a-policy-configuration-file

Closes-Bug: #1254461
Change-Id: I833db8385c2d3e8962a9c19b77c94d962eac475e

'}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2013-11-08 15:13:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Plugins override the definition of delete_port, do whatever "extra" they need to do, then call super().

Can you help me understand the benefit of adding **kwargs when most plugins follow the above convention, and this change does not make NeutronDbPluginV2 or any of the other classes utilize kwargs?'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-11-10 23:35:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

neutron_plugin_base_v2 class defines a minimum plugin API. The minimum plugin API is the API for Neutron core resources (networks, subnets, ports). db_plugin_v2 is same. It defines db operations for neutron core resources. Thus I don't think this change is needed. IMO extra arguments are allowed as long as it does not break the minimum signature of each plugin method."}, {'account_id': 7170, 'date': '2013-11-11 07:41:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

If the api does not accept extra arguments, the call to api shouldn't pass any extra arguments; but the db mixin passes l3_port_check without knowing which plugin it is calling.

If the api is kept unchanged, we should remove these extra arguments, as they do not follow the api. If a new plugin doesn't override delete_port, passing extra argument will causing exceptions"}, {'account_id': 2031, 'date': '2013-11-18 01:31:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Fix delete_port definition

Some derived plugins may pass some extra arguments to the delete
port call, so the api should accept extra arguments

Change-Id: I94d4c1291d5103659fca19dcc7112dbb32f95c12
Closes-Bug: #1248820

I'll try to elaborate on need to use cfg.CONF.host instead of this id forged with br-int mac address:

Currently, when a port is migrated, the very last message plugin will recieve regarding this port is an update_device_down from the original agent (after the update_device_up is reieved from the target agent). As a consequence, port status will remain to down in database (this is the bug Mathieu was referring to in the previous comment). The recently introduced l2-population feature also relies on accurate port status management, this is why we'd like to fix these migration issues.

The straightforward way to fix this issue would be to filter update_devices_up/down on plugin side to only allow agent on which port is bound to update its status (if nova manages to provide plugin with accurate port binding information when it migrate a VM, see [1]). The issue is that currently plugin has no way to figure out from which agent such messages are coming, as agent_id which is being build here for RPC messages isn't known (neither used) by plugin.

For sure, this bugfix could be taken as is, but in that case we'll probably have to change it back in the future, this is why we were proposing to do it here, as using cfg.CONF.host would help solving both issues."}, {'account_id': 6522, 'date': '2013-09-18 02:36:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 30:

Thanks Francois, for the clarification. 

To further clarify when you state. "probably have to change it back in the future". Are you referring to change the agent id to something that better consistently identifies an agent running per host?

I've opened bug/1226915 to  take of this issue as I've understood it so far. Please let me know, if I've misunderstood.'}, {'account_id': 6820, 'date': '2013-09-18 10:08:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 30:

I discussed with Mathieu and it finally turned out that it may be preferable to keep agent_id as is and add another host_id kwarg to fix migrated port status. Using another argument will allow plugin to only filter out agents that send host_id, whereas if we change agent_id to return cfg.CONF.host, plugin would filter out all updates sent by an agent that wouldn't have been fixed.

So please go ahead, and sorry for the noise..."}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2013-09-19 17:39:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 30: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Setting up ovs agent, create bridge if DNE

When starting ovs agent, and ovs integration bridge
does not exist, agent crashes. OVSBridge should always
create bridge if does not exist.

Fixes Bug: #1222954
Change-Id: Id3adf4aad03ed4573857776ec92dabb0d24d0514

'}, {'account_id': 6447, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

I want to summarize what I try to achieve and where we are now.
The patch makes sure that the driver method 'delete_pool(..)' is not invoked before lbaas plugin makes sure that the pool is not connected to a vip. (https://github.com/openstack/quantum/blob/master/quantum/services/loadbalancer/plugin.py#L114)
So I have added the '_validate_pool_not_in_use(..)' to loadbalancer_db.py.
The same validation should happen inside the method 'delete_pool' of loadbalancer_db.py (https://github.com/openstack/quantum/blob/master/quantum/db/loadbalancer/loadbalancer_db.py#L525)

So we have a short validation code that should be called twice. Therefore I used a method.
We have 2 options to validate that the pool is not connected to a vip. We can query the vips table or query the pools table. I think that if we query the pools table we can resue the pool_db object. I will commit a code that does it."}, {'account_id': 6447, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (2 inline comments)

The purpose of this patch is to validate that the pool is not connected to a vip before lbaas plugin call the lbaas driver and ask it to remove the pool. This will make sure we do not get into a situation where the pool was removed from the LB device but can not be removed from Quantum DB because it is connected to a vip.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Works for me

commit_message:
Revert "heatclient is not working with os-auth-token"

This reverts commit 4eab568f79bdbfe4ba0d31038bf3c253d0858c59.

The commit breaks the unit tests (and for some reason still passed
the gate...?), and also doesn't fix the issues with auth_token, ref
bug #1252248.  So revert this patch, while I work on a more
comprehensive fix to the auth_token issues.

Change-Id: I34b9e808928d091384c4c466f14260252a45fd2e
Closes-Bug: 1252313

commit_message:
Replace stubout with fixtures

blueprint remove-mox

The last step in removing mox is to remove stubout usage. Lucky for us,
the fixtures library, which we are already using, can take on the
challenge quite well.

Change-Id: Id33cc8988935a1905f9a14351964f0bb24ef82e3

commit_message:
Introduce the deployment

This patch involves the deployment as a new entity that represents all
operations on an installation. Also, this patch only introduce the
deployment on several levels and keeps the legacy logic of the task
workflow. So, it's not the separation but only preparation for that.

The copy of log_task_wrapper was created to use the legacy approach of
logging.

Removed unused statuses from the class rally.consts._TaskStatus, some of
them moved to the rallyconsts._DeployStatus.

Change-Id: Ibb90977e68dcd8ba1224b1ff6951d2c0bd7dbf9e
Implements: blueprint independent-deploy

commit_message:
Pass the size when fetching image in xenapi driver

In commit 6e287c0f2bb7d4994d50f1763f412277e4dac6f7 the fetch_to_raw
method was changed to accept the volume size so it can fail when the
image doesn't fit in the destination volume. In this commit we also
updated all the volume drivers to pass the volume size to that method so
it could perform the check. The xenapi driver missed that change.

This commit updates the xenapi driver to pass the volume size when
fetching the image to enable the introduced check.

Change-Id: I89bc4b3b1c1e6b06f5c529166cf9ffa1fe600c96
Related-Bug: #1235358

commit_message:
NetApp fix free space as zero during 1st vol stats update

NetApp clustered ontap drivers report space as zero
till first 60 seconds of driver start. This is causing
discomfort for some performance sensitive deployements.
This was due to async nature of the NetApp stats collection job.
Job is changed to sync at driver start to improve customer
experience.

Change-Id: I7d5cbf590897a0d328ece3a60516c92c0ad0ee7f
Closes-bug: #1253660

commit_message:
Initialize and terminate connection raise 500 err

Initialize and terminate connection should check whether "connector" is
in request body. It throws 500 error if "connector" is not present. We
should catch the KeyError and transfer it to 400 (HTTPBadRequest)
instead of.

Closes-Bug: #1253944
Change-Id: If38419592701c8a14df52f94fd46ed0fc7a17e04

commit_message:
Migrate volume should check para "host" in request

The server doesn't check whether the parameter "host" is in request
body. So the 500 error has been thrown.

We should catch the KeyError and transfer the KeyError to
400 (HTTPBadRequest) instead of 500.

Closes-Bug: #1253904
Change-Id: I3fb07113816a87f284b47e32bacd57f78a32676c

commit_message:
Adds negative tests to glance api's

It adds negative tests to get_image and delete_image
api's

get / delete -- non-existent image
get / delete -- image where id is null
get / delete -- deleted image
also moves test_get_image_null_id to negative file.

Change-Id: I239084b273e72dca98cb5813af4d8422d66daa5c

[{'created': '2013-11-22 15:15:54.000000000', 'message': 'Fix ./run_tests.sh -V --virtual-env-name

Currently if --virtual-env-name is specified, the tests fail
because it still creates .venv/ but then looks in the specified
location to use the venv.

This makes --virtual-env-name work as expected.

Change-Id: I036cd08f7b7b9dc87e7012f8dd198a26375297a2
'}]
commit_message:
Fix ./run_tests.sh -V --virtual-env-name

Currently if --virtual-env-name is specified, the tests fail
because it still creates .venv/ but then looks in the specified
location to use the venv.

This makes --virtual-env-name work as expected.

Change-Id: I036cd08f7b7b9dc87e7012f8dd198a26375297a2

commit_message:
Add hacking rules for shell scripts

This is an attempt to collect the rules that we live by in devstack
that are generally held. Writing these down help us figure out ways
to put them into bash8 over time. These are a starting point for
conversation.

Change-Id: Id2b750665871ebbeddf4694ba080c75d2f6f443e

commit_message:
More logging around console logs in libvirt

Bug 1251920 is causing heaps of check and gate failures, but we
don't have enough debug logging to really tell what's happening.
Add more logging.

Change-Id: Ibd7e658b1e5cfb99d09428c02da03ab47cb5e71c

commit_message:
Opt-out of service catalog

Introducing a config option 'include_service_catalog' to indicate whether
service catalog is needed. If the 'include_service_catalog' option is set to
False, middleware will not ask for service catalog on token validation and will
not set the X-Service-Catalog header.

This option is backward compatible as it is default to True.

DocImpact
Fixed bug 1228317

Change-Id: Id8c410a7ae0443ac425d20cb9c6a24ee5bb2cb8d

commit_message:
Make sure ssh retries on paramiko.SSHException

We are occasionally seeing paramiko raise a SSHException which is
causing tempest to fail out, but on a constrained devstack environment
its possible that there are network or other performance issues, so we
want to keep retrying on an SSHException just like we retry on a
paramiko.AuthenticationException.

Attempt at Closes-Bug: #1253896

Change-Id: I4293f9a47a6d524ced0d09eb67a52c5ed1ad361e

commit_message:
Cleanup using about the data_utils module and functions

 HACKING officially discourages symbol import directly because it makes
it harder to track down that a function was imported. Recently, we keep
this rule but there are many code that don't keep it.
 This commit cleanups them.

Change-Id: Ibda1a5e424280bad8535ee27f66dec99bf68f676

commit_message:
Ensure 'status' in update_snapshot_status

The function os-update_snapshot_status doesn't check whether the param
"status" is in request body. It throws 500 error. We should catch the
KeyError and return 400 (HTTPBadRequest) instead.

Change-Id: If3775e3c0299cf0edbdda5081a6633b38462011b

commit_message:
Adds support for json output to nova client

This change adds an option --json to the cli which enables
output as a json formatted string. This will be helpful
for automating scripts using the cli client.

Change-Id: I09ba98fa6a3e7dc038d0a8802641d71f115868d1
Closes-Bug: #1254351

commit_message:
Reuse a server instance in test_disk_config

In test_disk_config.py, each test creates a server instance everytime.
By applying this patch, a server instance is reused without a new server
creation if the existing server has necessary status.

Change-Id: I1e1f03df3b0d7840b6af666dbb412a7fea2ccbba

commit_message:
Stop using openstack.common.exception

The openstack.common.exception has been deprecated and removed from
oslo-incubator. Therefore, Keystone should follow the recommendation
and stop the usage of this file altogether.

DocImpact

Closes-Bug: #1208734
Change-Id: I7871657878acdb11c99954c755b01ed1969fc2e0

commit_message:
Quote URL in curl output to handle query params

Copy and pasting the generated curl output into a shell doesn't
work when the URL includes an ampersand, as the URL isn't quoted.

Closes-Bug: #1249891
Change-Id: Ic3d7682a2c034e89c3367c858ea33510f8cbc7d4

commit_message:
Fix curl debug output for requests with a body

Rather than output the request body as a separate line, make it part of
the example curl command using the -d option.

Partial-Bug: #1249891
Change-Id: Ie3fe4535f554333c67244a13c5698c025f000e7e

commit_message:
Remove service type restriction from keystone client help text

The current output of "keystone help service-create" implies that the
type is restricted to certain values.  This commit updates the help
text to make it more clear that the value isn't validated.

Closes bug 1248658
Closes bug 1211292

Change-Id: Ice4bf0da135d371ab5b6339f7baac7309e9c40ce
